/*------------------------------------*\
  $HEADINGS
\*------------------------------------*/
/**
 * Headings
 *
 * ##### Acceptable Use
 *
 * Use headings in the correct hierarchical manner (`<h1>` followed by `<h2>`, and so on)
 * as this improves readability and scannability for all users.
 *
 * ##### Avoid
 *
 * Do not use headings to achieve visual results only (e.g. skipping heading levels
 * because the lower degree heading matches the desired look).
 *
 * Do not use text formatting, such as font size or bold, to give the visual appearance of
 * a heading when it is not a heading.
 *
 * ##### Accessibility
 *
 * Screen readers can navigate to any heading on the page. All headings should be
 * descriptive and unique.
 *
 * Use headings (even visually hidden ones) to help screen readers navigate a complex
 * page or DOM structure.
 *
 * @section
 * @sectionof Typography
 *
 * @example
 * <h1>Heading Level 1</h1>
 * <h2>Heading Level 2</h2>
 * <h3>Heading Level 3</h3>
 * <h4>Heading Level 4</h4>
 * <h5>Heading Level 5</h5>
 */

 /**
 * Heading Classes
 *
 * ##### Acceptable Use
 *
 * You may style headings to look like other headings in order to achieve aesthetic visual
 * design but keep correct hierarchical structure (e.g. style an `<h1>` to look like an
 * `<h3>`).
 *
 * ##### Avoid
 *
 * Do not apply the heading classes to elements that are not headings (e.g. `<div>`).
 *
 * Do not use the Campaign Heading except for campaign pages.
 *
 * @section
 * @sectionof Typography
 *
 * @example
 * <h1 class="fs-h5">H1 styled as H5</h1>
 * <h2 class="fs-h4">H2 styled as H4</h2>
 * <h3 class="fs-h3">H3 styled as H3</h3>
 * <h4 class="fs-h2">H4 styled as H2</h4>
 * <h5 class="fs-h1">H5 styled as H1</h5>
 * <h1 class="fs-h1--campaign">Campaign Heading</h1>
 */

/*
 * 1. Increase letter spacing to improve readability for users with dyslexia. Tested
 *    with a user with dyslexia.
 * 2. Default heading font to verdana and lazy load with museo
 * 3. If browser doesn't support custom properties then we won't lazy load the font
 */
h1,
h2,
h3,
h4,
.fs-h1,
.fs-h2,
.fs-h3,
.fs-h4 {
  color: $color-grey;
  font-family: $font-face-body; /* [3] */
  font-family: var(--fs-font-face-heading, $font-face-body) /* [2, 3] */
  font-weight: normal;
  margin: 0;
}

html.museo-loaded {
  --fs-font-face-heading: $font-face-heading; /* [2] */
}

h1,
.fs-h1 {
  font-size: $font-size-large-xxx;
  letter-spacing: 0.06rem; /* [1] */
  line-height: $line-height-large-xxx;
}

h2,
.fs-h2 {
  font-size: $font-size-large-xx;
  letter-spacing: 0.05rem; /* [1] */
  line-height: $line-height-large-xx;
}

h3,
.fs-h3 {
  font-size: $font-size-large-x;
  letter-spacing: 0.04rem; /* [1] */
  line-height: $line-height-large-x;
  margin: 0 0 0.203125rem 0;
}

h4,
.fs-h4 {
  font-size: $font-size-large;
  letter-spacing: 0.04rem; /* [1] */
  line-height: $line-height-large;
}

h5,
h6,
.fs-h5,
.fs-h6 {
  @extend $h5;
}

.fs-h1--campaign {
  font-size: $font-size-large-xxxx;
  line-height: $line-height-large-xxxx;
}


/*------------------------------------*\
  $PARAGRAPHS
\*------------------------------------*/
/**
 * Paragraphs
 *
 * ##### Avoid
 *
 * Do not use any font size smaller than the standard paragraph size for any text (other
 * than captions and labels).
 *
 * ##### Accessibility
 *
 * When possible, place the distinguishing information of a paragraph in the first
 * sentence to help improve the scannability of content for all users.
 *
 * @section
 * @sectionof Typography
 *
 * @example
 * <p>A paragraph (from the Greek paragraphos, "to write beside" or "written beside") is a
 * self-contained unit of a discourse in writing dealing with a particular point or idea.
 * A paragraph consists of one or more sentences. Though not required by the syntax of any
 * language, paragraphs are usually an expected part of formal writing, used to organize
 * longer prose.</p>
 */
p {
  font-size: $font-size-medium;
  line-height: $line-height-medium;
  margin: 0;
}

// lobotomized owl variant
// http://alistapart.com/article/axiomatic-css-and-lobotomized-owls
p + * {
  margin-top: unit($baseline-grid, 'rem');
}





/*------------------------------------*\
  $ANCHORS
\*------------------------------------*/
/**
 * Links
 *
 * ##### Acceptable Use
 *
 * Use links only when the link will cause the user to navigate to a different page or
 * somewhere within the same page. Another way to think of it – if the URL changes,
 * you can use a link.
 *
 * ##### Avoid
 *
 * Do not use links when the only purpose is to use it to activate JavaScript (i.e. when
 * the `href` is equal to `#` or `javascript:void(0);`). Use a [button](#buttons) instead.
 *
 * ##### Accessibility
 *
 * Screen readers can navigate to any link on the page. All links should be descriptive
 * and unique.
 *
 * If your link just says "Read More," you should either put more description on
 * the link for all users or add visually hidden text just for the screen reader.
 * For example:
 *
 * ```html
 * Read More <span class="visually-hidden">about John Doe</span>
 * ```
 *
 * @section
 * @sectionof Typography
 *
 * @example
 * <p><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="standard-link">This is a text link</a></p>
 * <p><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="visited-link">This is a visited text link</a></p>
 *
 * @code
 * <p><a href="javascript:void(0)">This is a text link</a></p>
 * <p><a href="javascript:void(0)">This is a visited text link</a></p>
 */
a {
  text-decoration: none;

  &:hover {
    text-decoration: underline;
  }
}

a,
a:hover,
a:active,
a:focus {
  color: $color-blue-link;
}

a:visited {
  color: $color-purple-link-visited;
}





/*------------------------------------*\
  $INLINE_ELEMENTS
\*------------------------------------*/
/**
 * Inline Elements
 *
 * ##### Avoid
 *
 * Do not use `<small>` as a stand alone element just for small text. It should only be used
 * inline with other text.
 *
 * @section
 * @sectionof Typography
 *
 * @example
 * <p><strong>Strong is used to indicate strong importance</strong></p>
 * <p><em>Emphasized or italicized text</em></p>
 * <p>Superscript<sup>®</sup></p>
 * <p>Subscript for things like H<sub>2</sub>O</p>
 * <p><small>This small text is small for fine print, etc.</small></p>
 */
button {
  font-family: $font-face-body;
}

/*
 * Inline elements inherit their line-height from their parents (or default to normal if
 * no parent defines one). This means you cannot set the line-height of an inline element.
 *
 * However, if the element is removed from the normal document flow (via display:table-cell,
 * position:absolute, float:left, etc.), the line-height can be set. Because of this, we will
 * set the line-height for those cases when it is removed from the document flow, but
 * understand that it won't apply in the majority of cases.
 */
small {
  font-size: $font-size-small;
  line-height: $line-height-small;
  color: $color-grey-light;
}





/**
 * Lists
 * @section
 */

/**
 * Unordered Lists
 *
 * ##### Avoid
 *
 * Do not use lists to merely indent or for other layout purposes.
 *
 * ##### Accessibility
 *
 * Screen readers can navigate to any list on the page and even jump from list item
 * to list item within a list. Use lists to allow screen readers to navigate between
 * groups of items easily (such as a list of persons).
 *
 * You can label a list so screen readers know what the list is by using `aria-label`
 * or `aria-labeledby=[id]` on the `<ul>` element.
 *
 * @section
 * @sectionof Lists
 *
 * @example
 * <ul>
 *   <li>This is a list item in an unordered list</li>
 *   <li>An unordered list is a list in which the sequence of items is not important. Sometimes, an unordered list is a bulleted list. And this is a long list item in an unordered list that can wrap onto a new line. </li>
 *   <li>Lists can be nested inside of each other
 *     <ul>
 *       <li>This is a nested list item</li>
 *       <li>This is another nested list item in an unordered list</li>
 *     </ul>
 *   </li>
 *   <li>This is the last list item</li>
 * </ul>
 */

/**
 * Ordered Lists
 *
 * The criteria for [Unordered Lists](#lists-unordered-lists) also applies to Ordered
 * Lists.
 *
 * @section
 * @sectionof Lists
 *
 * @example
 * <ol>
 *   <li>This is a list item in an ordered list</li>
 *   <li>An ordered list is a list in which the sequence of items is important. An ordered list does not necessarily contain sequence characters.</li>
 *   <li>
 *     Lists can be nested inside of each other
 *     <ol>
 *       <li>This is a nested list item</li>
 *       <li>This is another nested list item in an ordered list</li>
 *     </ol>
 *   </li>
 *   <li>This is the last list item</li>
 * </ol>
 */
ol, ul, li {
  line-height: $line-height-medium;
  padding: 0;
}

ol, ul {
  margin: 0 0 $line-height-medium $line-height-medium;
}

li {
  margin: 0;
}